\f0\b\fs48 \cf0 Introduction
\f1\fs36 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\f0\b0\fs30 \cf0 Puppet is an open source IT management tool written in Ruby, used for datacenter automation and server management at Google, Twitter, the New York Stock Exchange, and many others. \'a0It is primarily maintained by Puppet Labs, which also founded the project. \'a0Puppet can manage as few as 2 machines and as many as 50,000, on teams with one system administrator or hundreds.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 Puppet is a tool for configuring and maintaining your computers: \'a0In its simple configuration language, you explain to Puppet how you want your machines configured, and it changes them as needed to match your specification. \'a0As you change that specification over time -- such as with package updates, new users, or configuration updates -- Puppet will automatically update your machines to match. \'a0If they are already configured as desired, then Puppet does nothing.\
\
In general, Puppet does everything it can to use existing system features to do its work; e.g., on Red Hat it will yum for packages and init.d for services, but on OS X it will use dmg for packages and launchd for services.  One of the guiding goals in Puppet is to have the work it does make sense whether you are looking at Puppet code or the system itself, so following system standards is critical.\
\
Puppet comes from multiple traditions of other tools.  In the open source world, it is most influenced by Cfengine, which was the first open source general-purpose configuration tool, and ISconf, whose use of 'make' for all work inspired the focus on explicit dependencies throughout the system.  In the commercial world, Puppet is a response to BladeLogic and Opsware (both since acquired by larger companies), each of which was successful in the market when Puppet was begun but each of which was focused on selling to executives at large companies rather than building great tools directly for system administrators.  Puppet is meant to solve similar problems to these tools, but it is focused on a very different user.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 For a simple example of how to use Puppet, here is a snippet of code that will make sure the secure shell service (SSH) is installed and configured properly:
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 	class ssh \{
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 		package \{ ssh: ensure => installed \}
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 		file \{ \'93/etc/ssh/sshd_config\'94:
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1920\fi960

\f0\fs30 \cf0 source => \'93ssh/sshd_config\'94,
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 ensure => present,
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 require => Package[ssh]
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 \}
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1920

\f0\fs30 \cf0 service \{ sshd:
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 	ensure => running,
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 	require => [File[\'93/etc/ssh/sshd_config\'94], Package[ssh]]
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 \}
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\f0\fs30 \cf0 	\}
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 This makes sure the package is installed, the file is in place, and the service is running. \'a0Note that we\'92ve specified dependencies between the resources, so that we always perform any work in the right order. \'a0\'a0This class could then be associated with any host to apply this configuration on it. \'a0Notice that the building blocks of a Puppet configuration are structured objects, in this case \'91package\'92, \'91file\'92, and \'91service\'92. \'a0We call these objects \'91resources\'92 in Puppet, and everything in a Puppet configuration comes down to these resources and the dependencies between them.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 A normal Puppet site will have tens or even hundreds of these code snippets, which we call \'91classes\'92; we store these classes on disk in files called \'91manifests\'92, and collect them in related groups called \'91modules\'92. For instance, you might have an \'91ssh\'92 module with this \'91ssh\'92 class plus any other related classes, along with modules for \'91mysql\'92, \'91apache\'92, and \'91sudo\'92.\
\
Most Puppet interactions are via the command line or long-running HTTP services, but there are graphical interfaces for some things, such as report processing.  Puppet Labs also produces commercial products around Puppet, which tend more toward graphical web-based interfaces.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 Puppet's first prototype was written in the summer of 2004, and it was turned into a full-time focus in February of 2005. \'a0It was initially designed and written by Luke Kanies, a sysadmin who had done a lot of experience writing small tools, but none writing tools greater than 10,000 lines of code. \'a0In essence, Luke learned to be a programmer while writing Puppet, and that shows in both positive and negative ways in its architecture.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 Puppet was first and foremost built to be a tool for sysadmins, to be something that made their lives easier and allowed them to work faster, more efficiently, and with fewer errors. \'a0The first key innovation meant to deliver on this was a set of primitives, which we call \'91resources\'92, that would both be portable across most operating systems and also abstract away implementation detail, allowing the user to focus on outcomes rather than how to achieve them. \'a0This set of primitives was implemented in Puppet's Resource Abstraction Layer.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 Puppet resources must be unique on a given host. \'a0You can only have one package named \'91ssh\'92, one service named \'91sshd\'92, and one file named \'91/etc/ssh/sshd_config\'92. \'a0This prevents different parts of your configurations from conflicting with each other, and you find out about those conflicts very early in the configuration process. \'a0We refer to these resources by their type and title; e.g., Package[ssh] and Service[sshd]. \'a0You have a package and a service with the same name, because they are different types, but not two packages or services.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 The second key innovation in Puppet provides the ability to directly specify dependencies between resources. \'a0Previous tools focused on the individual work to be done, rather than how the various bits of work were related, and Puppet was the first tool to explicitly say that dependencies were a first-class part of your configurations and must be modeled that way. \'a0It built a graph of resources and their dependencies as one of the core data types, and essentially everything in Puppet hangs off of this graph (which is called a Catalog, in Puppet parlance) and its vertices and edges.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 The last major component in Puppet is its configuration language. \'a0This language is declarative, and is meant to be more configuration data than full programming - it most resembles Nagios's configuration format, but is also heavily influenced by Cfengine and ruby.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 Beyond the functional components, Puppet has had two guiding principles throughout its development: \'a0It should be as simple as possible, always preferring usability even at the expense of capability, and it should be built as a framework first and application second, so that others could build their own applications on Puppet's internals as desired. \'a0It was understood that Puppet's framework needed a killer application to be adopted widely, but the framework was always the focus, not the application. \'a0Most people think of Puppet as being that application, rather than the framework behind it.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 When Puppet's prototype was first built, Luke was essentially a decent Perl programmer with a lot of shell experience and some C experience, mostly consisting of working in Cfengine. \'a0The odd bit is he had experience building parsers for simple languages, having built two as part of smaller tools and also having rewritten Cfengine's parser from scratch in an effort to make it more maintainable (this code was never submitted back, because of small incompatibilities).\

\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 A dynamic language was easily decided on for Puppet's implementation, based on much higher developer productivity and time to market, but choosing the language proved difficult. \'a0Initial prototypes in Perl went nowhere, so other languages were sought for experimentation. \'a0Python was tried, but Luke found the language quite at odds with how he thought about the world. \'a0Based on what amounted to a rumor of utility heard from a friend, Luke tried Ruby, and in four hours had built a usable prototype. \'a0When Puppet became a full time effort in 2005, Ruby was a complete unknown, so the decision to stick with it was a big risk, but again, programmer productivity was deemed the primary driver in language choice. \'a0The major distinguishing feature in Ruby, at least as opposed to Perl, was how easy it was to build non-hierarchical class relationships, but it also mapped very well to Luke\'92s brain, which turned out to be critical.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280

\f0\b\fs48 \cf0 Architectural Overview
\f1\fs36 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\f0\b0\fs30 \cf0 This chapter is primarily about the architecture of Puppet's implementation (that is, the code that we've used to make Puppet do the things it's supposed to do) but it's worth briefly discussing its application architecture (that is, how the parts communicate), so that the implementation makes some sense.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 Puppet has been built with two modes in mind: \'a0A client/server mode with a central server and agents running on separate hosts, or a serverless mode where a single process does all of the work. \'a0To ensure consistency between these modes, Puppet has always had network transparency internally, so that the two modes used the same code paths whether they went over the network or not. \'a0Each executable can configure local or remote service access as appropriate, but otherwise they behave identically. \'a0Note also that you can use the serverless mode in what amounts to a client/server configuration, by pulling all configuration files to each client and having it parse them directly. \'a0This section will focus on the client/server mode, because it\'92s more easily understood as separate components, but keep in mind that this is all true of the serverless mode, also.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 One of the defining choices in Puppet\'92s application architecture is that the clients should not get access to raw Puppet modules; instead, they get a configuration compiled just for them. \'a0This provides multiple benefits: \'a0First, you follow the principle of least privilege, in that each host only knows exactly what it needs to know (how it should be configured), but it does not know how any other servers are configured. \'a0Second, you can completely separate the rights needed to compile a configuration (which might include access to central data stores) from the need to apply that configuration. \'a0Third, you can run hosts in a disconnected mode, where they repeatedly apply a configuration with no contact to a central server, which means you remain in compliance even if the server is down or the client is disconnected (such as would be the case in a mobile installation, or when the clients are in a DMZ).
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs30 Given this choice, the workflow becomes relatively straightforward:
